Introduction
The Bank of Canada is working to get inflation rates back to the target level of 2%.
1
It has
identified possible risks that may occur in the near future that would hinder achieving this. The
five key risks mentioned are:
• Stronger Household Spending in Canada
• Additional Fiscal Stimulus in the United States
• Persistent Cost Pressures
• Corporate Financial Stress
• Stronger Canadian Dollar
The second part of this brief consists of an analysis of these risks. Each risk will be summarized,
and data will be presented if it appears that this risk has manifested itself since the publication
of the January 2021 Report. Recommended policy actions in order to mitigate these inflationary
pressures will also be discussed.
Stronger Household Spending in Canada
The Bank of Canada January 2021 Monetary Policy Report identified that household savings
have increased to unusually high amounts during the pandemic. They speculated that this is
probably due to less opportunities to spend since to lockdown measures have been
implemented. People are also being more cautious of saving in unprecedented times. The risk
is that people may spend these accumulated savings rather than use them for investment or debt
payment, which means consumption could be stronger than the projected values. The economy
would then face less disinflationary pressure.
1
See Figure 5 for detailed chart on CPI measures of the inflation rate which will be used as reference for

2
In March the Bank of Canada gave an update on the situation of household savings and
spending during the COVID-19 pandemic entitled “COVID-19, savings and household
spending”.
2
In Chart 3 of this document it appears that spending sharply declined in the second
half of 2020. Canadians are overall spending less than normal, and mostly on essentials (e.g.
food and clothing), transport services and recreational services, and hospitality, with very little
spend on shelter and non-essentials. The overall spending slowly increased over the third and
fourth quarter, and the Bank of Canada predicts that this will increase into the first quarter of
2021. Without much day to day change in the pandemic situation, it is likely the inflationary
pressure from the additional spending won’t be observed until Canadians are able to go out and
spend their savings with the guarantee of employment income as well.
The low interest rate the Bank of Canada has established would not counteract this
effect, it will in fact encourage spending and investing further. At the moment with the
Canadian economy recovering from the COVID-19 recession, additional consumer spending
would be welcomed to create greater growth for the economy. In the January 2021 Monetary
Policy Report, the Bank of Canada mentions how consumption will underpin the recovery of
the Canadian economy. From the Canadian Survey of Consumer Expectations
3
half of
respondents intended to be more cautious with savings well into 2021. Overall it seems that
this risk is an unlikely one to occur given the data the bank has gathered so far on consumers’
intentions. It would appear that keeping the inflation rate low as is, is probably the best course
of action at the moment. Less disinflationary pressure from increased household spending is
exactly what the Canadian economy will need over the next year or so to fully recover.

Additional Fiscal Stimulus in the United States
The January 2021 Monetary Policy Report mentions that the United States government has
proposed an additional fiscal stimulus package for the country on top of the $900 billion
approved since the October Report. It further mentions that if the fiscal stimulus were to be
approved, it would mean that the United States’ economic growth could be greater than
originally predicted. Canada’s largest trading partner is with the United States. The growth of
the United States economy would cause an increase in Canadian exports and investments, and
this would create an inflationary pressure on the Canadian economy. This is also considered
an upside risk like that of stronger household spending.
The checks from the stimulus package have been sent out to U.S. citizens as of March
17th 2021. This is still very recent and many U.S. business owners are still uncertain that this
financial aid could prevent shutting down their businesses permanently.
4
Statistics Canada
reported in April 2021 that Canada’s exports to the United State has increased by 10.5% in
January 2021 and again by 0.8% in February 2021.
5
The initiation of the stimulus package is
quite recent, but it is likely that it will facilitate further exports to the U.S. given the trend of
increased in exports.
It seems that inflationary pressure is really what the Bank of Canada is trying to focus
on in order to avoid deflation. If the United States economy were to grow and then consequently
increase Canadian exports and investments leading to inflation then this would be most
welcome. Especially considering that the same Statistics Canada also indicated that exports to
the whole world decreased in February by 2.7%.
6
It seems that once again the best course of
action would be to keep the interest rate low in order to promote inflation and avoid deflation.

Persistent Cost Pressures
Lockdown measures and fear of contracting the virus has been disrupting businesses in all
types of industry. The January 2021 report most importantly noted how manufacturing firms
are likely to change their production processes due to the pandemic disrupting regular supply-
chain operations. In the long-term the structural changes across firms would lead to persistent
cost pressures, and therefore the Canadian economy would experience more inflationary
pressure.
Business operation disruption has been observed as most severe for certain industries,
such as: accommodation, food, arts, entertainment, recreation, transportation and warehousing.
The demand for oil has also sharply decreased due to the decrease in demand for travel. As of
December 2020 the real GDP for these sectors have yet to recover to half their original values
at the start of January 2020.
7
The employment level for these sectors have also shifted
dramatically. In the accommodation and food services industries, about 137,000 people have
left their jobs between September 2020 and February 2021.
8
The restructuring of these sectors, although only necessary due to the pandemic which
also caused a recession, may also be helpful in the economy’s recovery. The prolonged
spending required to sustain the restructuring which will mostly likely occur over the duration
of the pandemic as well as follow after it has passed. This further investment and spending
would work similarly to increased housing spending by creating an inflationary pressure which
7

8
See Figure 2
5
is what the Bank of Canada needs. It would make sense for the Bank of Canada to not interfere
with this mass restructuring as it would help get the inflation rate back to its target level.
Corporate Financial Stress
The pandemic has caused many businesses to shut down temporarily, or end up closing their
doors indefinitely. Because of this, The Bank of Canada inferred that many businesses are
facing severe cash flow pressures, and the Canadian economy may face a large and sudden
number of bankruptcies. Credits conditions may ultimately be tightened and banks may
become reluctant to lend, while other businesses may be more conservative in their saving and
reluctant to take on new investments.
It seems that over 2020 there were unusual fluctuations in the business lending
conditions due to the pandemic. Yet, in the final quarter they seemed to have returned to pre-
pandemic levels.
9
This is a good indication that banks are becoming less reluctant to lend
despite still being cautious. That being said, there was a 6.4% increase in total insolvencies
across Canada from January 2021 to February 2021.
10
The Bank of Canada has established disinflationary pressures as downside risks given
the severely low inflation rate since the COVID-19 recession.
11
It seems that continuing to
keep the interest rate low is one of the safest and best options to counteract this specific risk.
The low interest rate should make it cheaper for businesses to spend and invest, thusly
incentivising them to do so. More business spending and investing should lead to a greater
aggregate demand in the economy which in turn should facilitate the inflation rate to steadily
rise.

6
Stronger Canadian Dollar
The Monetary Policy Report attributes the steady rise of the Canadian dollar from October
2020 to January 2021 to the broad based weakness of the US dollar. It stated that the Canadian
dollar has appreciated against the US dollar which has overall created a deflationary pressure
by lowering the prices of imports. This appreciation may also reduce the output growth by
making Canadian export and imports less competitive relative to competing production, which
could further the disinflationary pressure felt by the Canadian economy.
The strength of the Canadian dollar has been clearly exhibited by an appreciation of
about 3% against the U.S. dollar since January 2021. The CEER scales have both recovered
to their January 2020 values and continue to rise further into 2021. The CEER scale excluding
the U.S. rose from 121 to 126 from January 1st to March 25th, which is another indication of
the Canadian dollar appreciating against the currencies of other significant trading partners
with Canada. This may be a detriment to Canadian exporting firms, but beneficial to foreign
firms exporting into Canada.
12
Disinflationary pressure is not what the Bank of Canada would hope to occur as the
inflation rate is currently well below the target 2%. If the appreciation of the Canadian dollar
occurs faster than anticipated then the Bank of Canada may have to take action. One way that
it could directly do this is to manipulate the supply of Canadian dollars in foreign exchange
markets. The bank could sell Canadian dollars in foreign exchange markets and then buy up
other currencies, which would work to lower the price of the Canadian dollar.
